messages.content: so if i load balance, the miner can utilize them both as one?

not quite, the way load balancing works is it balances requests over both APIs, which in this case meaning over both GPUs
the way it's setup currently is each GPU handles *one* request concurrently(I do plan to make that configurable along with a lot of other changes), so when you load balance over two and get multiple requests, say 4, then 2 will go to one of them and the other 2 will go to the other one

so i can handle more requests at the same time, but not use both on one request

which does *overall* lower gen time, as then concurrent generations won't wait the whole generation duration before starting

The validation mechanism will receive a revamp soon that is as follows;
# Base weights & periodic validation
Miners will now have a base weight value that is calculated periodically via a queue, by default the validator pushes miners to the queue for evaluation based on if they don't base weights set or if they have not been checked in the most amount of blocks

The periodic evaluation uses a few metrics to set the base weight, mainly similarity for diffusion steps requested(like before), but no longer time, instead scaling by the maximum RPS the miner can handle under a time constraint, allowing miners' incentive to scale uncapped so long as the compute is available to handle the requests(meaning load balancing is greatly encouraged, along with configuring GPUs to generate multiple requests concurrently)

# User requests
When a validator chooses a miner for a user request, it does a few validation steps:
- If the miner fails to generate, it loses 15% weight
- If the miner has the base weight set, it receives a weight bonus and has a 25% chance to be added to the queue for periodic validation again(to ensure its responsiveness and quality remains)
- If the base weight is not set, it is pushed to the periodic validation queue for initial base weights

(Numbers here are not finalized)

The purpose of this is to reward higher throughput, and successful user requests, to allow the subnet to scale and hopefully handle load much more effectively than before
